This project tries to uncover the relationships among a set of varisbles; in particular, it shows if the economy and press freedom are good predictors of corruption control worldwide.

The data we have used was previously organized in Python, you can see that here.

Let us call the data:

dataLink="https://github.com/EvansDataScience/basicFinal_CompThink/raw/master/dataProject.csv"
df=read.csv(dataLink,stringsAsFactors = FALSE)

These are the contents:

str(df)
## 'data.frame':    153 obs. of  5 variables:
##  $ iso       : chr  "ALB" "DZA" "AGO" "ARG" ...
##  $ country   : chr  "Albania" "Algeria" "Angola" "Argentina" ...
##  $ corruption: int  39 34 18 36 33 79 75 30 43 26 ...
##  $ economy   : num  7.54 4.84 5.4 4.88 7.6 7.99 7.66 6.38 7.38 6.32 ...
##  $ press     : num  60 48.2 50 64.8 61.1 ...

The variable corruption behaves like this:

hist(df$corruption)

Let me see how each of the proposed predictors relates to our dependent variable:

plot(df$corruption,df$press)

plot(df$corruption,df$economy)

We know that the predictors have a fairly linear relationship with the dependent variable, then we can test our hypothesis by seeing the effect of each controlling by the other:

test=lm(as.numeric(corruption)~press+economy,data=df)

The result is shown here:

summary(test)

As we see above, our model is significant with a decent Adjusted R-squared:

summary(test)$adj.r.squared
## [1] 0.598232

Next, we need to verify some requisites so that our results are trustable.

  1. The residuals should seems normally distributed: for that we need to see them along the vertical of the qqplot.
# normality of residuals?
library(car)
qqPlot(test, main="QQ Plot")

  1. The error variance changes with the level of the response, which will happen if the output of the ncvTest function is non-significant.
# homocedastic?
ncvTest(test)
## Non-constant Variance Score Test 
## Variance formula: ~ fitted.values 
## Chisquare = 4.022599    Df = 1     p = 0.04489448
  1. The predictors are no highly correlated:
# collinearity?
vif(test) > 4 # problem?
##   press economy 
##   FALSE   FALSE
  1. Detect the change if influential observations are eliminated:
influencePlot(test, id.method = 'noteworthy', main="Influence Plot", sub="Circle size is proportial to Cook's Distance" )

##      StudRes        Hat     CookD
## 122 2.179466 0.07947023 0.1333587
## 149 2.131183 0.12762379 0.2163776
